{
  "text": "Studying patient outcomes in the multiligament knee injury population has posed a challenging task. These patients often have traumatic knee injuries, and some have concurrent fractures or nerve or vascular injuries. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] These combined factors are known to influence patient outcomes. Furthermore, studies evaluating the outcomes after PLC and ACL surgery try to combine staged surgery (performing the ACL reconstruction [ACLR] at a different time than the PLC repair or reconstruction) with combined surgery (performing the ACLR at the same time as the PLC is addressed) at different decision points after injury. Given these weaknesses, the current literature does not clearly support a single technique or surgical approach to these complex knee injuries.",
  "citation_candidates": [
